  "solution": {
    "approach": "The Fibonacci series can be generated iteratively. Starting with F0 = 0 and F1 = 1, each subsequent term is the sum of the two previous terms. For each test case we iterate N times, appending the current term to the output. Using Java's BigInteger avoids overflow for the 93‑rd term which exceeds signed 64‑bit range. The algorithm runs in linear time per test case and uses O(1) extra memory.",
    "timeComplexity": "O(N) per test case, O(total N) over all test cases.",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(1) auxiliary space (output not counted).",
    "code": {
      "C": "",
      "C++": "",
      "Java": "import java.io.*;\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));\n        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();\n        int T = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n        for (int tc = 0; tc < T; tc++) {\n            int N = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n            BigInteger a = BigInteger.ZERO;\n            BigInteger b = BigInteger.ONE;\n            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {\n                if (i == 0) {\n                    sb.append(a);\n                } else if (i == 1) {\n                    sb.append(' ').append(b);\n                } else {\n                    BigInteger c = a.add(b);\n                    sb.append(' ').append(c);\n                    a = b;\n                    b = c;\n                }\n            }\n            sb.append('\\n');\n        }\n        System.out.print(sb.toString());\n    }\n}",
      "Python3": "",
      "JavaScript": ""
    }
  },
